Currently, only the last number in a version is auto incremented (i.e. 1.0 will auto-increment to 1.1 for the next version).

It would be handy to be able to specify additional rules. For example, given:
{noformat}
1.{minor}{milestone}
{noformat}

- Deployment to the testing environment increments the milestone version (1.0\-m1 => 1.0\-m2)
- Deployment to production increments the minor version, and resets the milestone version (1.0\-m2 => 1.1\--m0-). The milestone version is hidden (1.1).
- Another deployment to testing increments the milestone version. (1.1\-m0 => 1.1\-m1)

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
I wanted to make a request for the Tomcat Undeploy task to have an optional "Ignore Undeploy Failure" feature so that if the webapp fails to undeploy it won't fail the build.

This would be immensely helpful in situations where you're deploying to a Tomcat server for the first time, or the last deployment failed for some reason and you want to re-run the deployment job without having to remember to go in and disable the Undeploy task.

An alternative would be a totally new task called something like, "Conditionally Undeploy" which only undeploys if there's a web app deployed at the given context root. 
{panel}

Currently the branch build results are combined with regular plan results, and it's confusing. For example, getting a branch name via a REST API call can be done by this call:
{code}
http://localhost:8085/rest/api/latest/result/PROJ1-PLAN11
{code}
and the shortName will contain the branch name:
{code}
...
<plan enabled="true" type="chain_branch" shortKey="PLAN11" shortName="master" name="Project-1 - Plan-1 - master" key="PROJ1-PLAN11">
...
{code}

Having a separate REST API service for plan branches will make working with them more straightforward.

I have defined a pattern on the default job of a plan to be {code}.*(\w+)\-(\w+).\.+.SUCCESS.* {code}

and then i chose the label to be \1 as defined by this doc 

https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Configuring+automatic+labelling+of+job+build+results

The plan does not get labeled even though there are two lines that satisfy this in the build log. Please advise me on how to use this option. Thanks.

{code}build	01-Jul-2013 16:18:51	[INFO] child-one ......................................... SUCCESS [2.124s]
build	01-Jul-2013 16:18:51	[INFO] child-two ......................................... SUCCESS [0.930s]{code}

It would be very convenient to know who and how ran the previous reruns of each build. Something like:
{code}
Changes by John Doe; Rebuilt 3 times by (1) Jane Doe, (2) Jack Doe, (3) Joe Doe
{code}

Using the installation instructions [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Bamboo+remote+agent+installation+guide], I am trying unsuccessfully to install an Agent to a Windows machine to a non-default location

This command runs successfully and installs a Windows Service for the agent:
{{java  -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.4.5.jar http://abc-bamboo01:8085/agentServer installntservice}}

However, it is creating a 'bamboo-agent-home' directory under the current user's profile. I want to relocate this directory.  
Following the installation instructions I have attempted many variations but get the same error:
{{Error: Could not find or load main class .home=D:\Bamboo\Home\}}

With the Jar file in the D:\Bamboo directory, I have tried:
{{java -Dbamboo.home=D:\\Bamboo\\Home\\ -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.4.5.jar...etc}}
{{java -Dbamboo.home=D:\Bamboo\Home\ -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.4.5.jar...etc}}
{{java -Dbamboo.home=Home -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.4.5.jar...etc}}
{{java -Dbamboo.home=D:/Bamboo/Home/ -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.4.5.jar...etc}}

Have also tried the above with "-Dbamboo-home", but without success.

The above commands were executed on Windows Server 2008 Standard, using Powershell, running as administrator.

For automated deployments of agents, the straightforward java -jar installer.jar execution leaves a couple things to be desired:

-1) base install path isn't definable; not really significant, in that moving the extracted bamboo-agent-home once extracted isn't hard, its just an extra step;- (forgot about -Dbamboo.home=RemoteAgentHome);
2) bamboo-agent-home doesn't canonically contain the version number of the bamboo version that installed it; this is different than most of the other atlassian products, in that installation of a new agent would either overwrite the existing directory, or be skipped, depending on how you detected whether an agent was already installed on a machine;
3) auto-starting the agent immediately on installation precludes any additional setup or configuration that may be tied to automated deployment; while its _possible_ to detect that the directory has been created, then kill the nascent process, then finish configuration, then restart the agent, simply accepting a -nostart option to the installer would make this much simpler.

There's naturally a 2nd way to do this, which is to pre-wrap the agent directory in a deployable package, and simply copy and un-tgz as needed, but the inclusion of:

{noformat}
<agentUuid>ddba1397-c1aa-48b4-ac0a-c0de85d5442e</agentUuid>
<agentDefinition>
<id>31916033</id>
<name>...</name>
</agentDefinition>
{noformat}

with no obvious mechanism for determining the handshake order of the uuid and id registration with the master makes that risky currently.

If its possibly to just generate any UUID prior to first connecting the agent to the master, then that should be easy, but the ID question remains, and in the end, I'd rather run the installer than risk having out of date packages or missed registration calls;

Just my 2 cents

